<section xml:id="introduction-to-discrete-time-dynamical-systems-dtds">
<title>Introduction to discrete-time dynamical systems
(DTDS)</title>


<paragraphs xml:id="the-plan-5">
<title>The Plan</title>

<p> We look at a powerful modeling technique that has subtle
connections to calculus.<!-- linebreak -->
</p>


<paragraphs xml:id="prediction">
<title>Prediction</title>

<p>	An important part of mathematics and science is
describing the mechanisms by which measurements change and making a
testable prediction.
</p>


<paragraphs
xml:id="approach-discrete-time-dynamical-systems">
<title>Approach: Discrete-time dynamical
systems</title>

<p> Used to predict measurements made at discrete
time intervals (e.g., measurements made once per hour, day, week).
Consider a measurement <m>m_t</m> made at time <m>t</m>, to define a
discrete-time dynamical system (DTDS) we write <me>m_{t+1} =
f(m_t).</me>
</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="yeast-growth">
<title>Yeast growth</title>

<p> Recall the data collected earlier this semester,
similar to what is presented below, that describe the growth of yeast
from one day to the next.
</p>

