</p>

<p> Let <m>y_t</m> denote the measured area
(mm<m>{}^{2}</m>) of the yeast measured on day <m>t</m>. Define the DTDS
that predicts the future measurement, called <m>y_{t+1}</m>.<!--
linebreak -->
</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="definition-solution">
<title>Definition â€“ solution</title>

<p> The sequence of values <m>m_t</m> for <m>t = 0,
1, 2, \dots</m> is the <term>solution</term> of the discrete-time
dynamical system <m>m_{t+1} = f(m_t)</m> starting from initial condition
<m>m_{0}</m>. We sometimes graph the solution as a plot of points
against
time.
</p>

<p> For our yeast growth predictions, example
initial conditions above were <m>y_{0}=100</m> mm<m>{}^{2}</m> and
<m>y_{0}=10</m> mm<m>{}^{2}</m>. Using the updating function, compute
five
terms of the solution starting from each of these initial
conditions.<!-- linebreak -->
</p>

<p> Starting from <m>y_{0}=100</m> mm<m>{}^{2}</m>
</p>

<p> Starting from <m>y_{0}=10</m> mm<m>{}^{2}</m>
</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="a-solution-formula">
<title>A solution formula</title>

<p> Sometimes we can write a formula for the
solution <m>y_t</m> to predict the population size at <em>any</em>
future time <m>t</m>.
</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="a-graphical-computer">
<title>A graphical computer</title>

<p> We have a powerful technique for studying the
behavior of such models using only a pencil and paper. This technique is
called cobwebbing, and its name will be come clear shortly.
</p>

<figure>
<image  xml:id = "image-graph-sample-yeast-data2" source="yeast_fall19b.png"/>
<caption>image</caption>
</figure>

<p> Note: you often <term>will not</term> have the
data points on this graph, so they have been removed.<!-- linebreak
-->This is how we <sq>cobweb</sq>:
</p>

<p><ol>
<li> <p> Graph the updating function and the diagonal
(the identity or line <m>y=x</m>)</p> </li>
<li> <p> Start at initial condition and go up or down to
the updating function and over to the diagonal</p> </li>
<li> <p> Repeat for as many steps as needed to find the
pattern</p> </li>
<li> <p> Sketch the solution at times <m>t=0, 1, 2,
\dots</m></p> </li>

</ol></p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="updating-and-inverses">
<title>Updating and inverses</title>

<p> What could we learn from the inverse of the
updating function to the DTDS <me>m_{t+1} = f(m_t)?</me>
</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="extra-dtds-examples">
<title>Extra DTDS examples</title>

<p> The following completely nonbiological examples
illustrate some interesting mathematical behaviors. These will help us
understand behaviors of more complicated biological models next
time.<!-- linebreak -->
</p>

<sidebyside>
<image  xml:id = "image-graph-linear-cobwebs"  source="linear_pos.png" width = "50%"/>

<image  xml:id = "image-graph-linear-cobwebs2" source="linear_neg.png" width = "50%"/>
<caption>Cobwebbing diagrams for some linear discrete-time dynamical systems.  These are not themselves biologically interesting, but emphasize the technique and have subtle connections to important applications.</caption>
</sidebyside>

<p> Each day a patient uses up half of the
medication in his bloodstream, but he is also given a new dose that
raises the concentration in the blood stream by 1 mg/L. Let <m>M_t</m>
denote the concentration on day <m>t</m>.
</p>

<p><ul>
<li> <p> Write a DTDS describing this situation and plot
the updating function.</p> </li>
<li> <p> What does the solution look like if you start
with <m>M_{0}</m> = 5 mg/L? <m>M_{0}</m> = 1 mg/L?</p> </li>

</ul></p>

<p> Plot the diagonal and updating function for the
previous model and cobweb five terms of the solution starting from
<m>M_{0}</m> = 5 mg/L and then from <m>M_{0}</m> = 1 mg/L.
</p>

<figure>
<image xml:id="image-blank-graph-dtds" source="graph.png"  width = "50%"/>
<caption>Blank graph paper for DTDS.</caption>
</figure>

<p> What happens if you start at <m>M_{0}=2</m>?
</p>

<p> A point <m>m^*</m> is called an equilibrium of
the DTDS <me>m_{t+1} = f(m_t)</me> if <m>f(m^*) = m^*</m> (i.e., if
updating by the DTDS leaves the input <m>m^*</m> unchanged).
</p>

<p><ul>
<li> <p> Find equilibria (more than 1 equilibrium)
graphically by locating the points where the graphs of the updating
function and diagonal intersect.</p> </li>
<li> <p> Find equilibria algebraically by setting
<m>f(m^*) = m^*</m> and solving for <m>m^*</m> .</p> </li>

</ul></p>

<p> Compute equilibrium values for the following
DTDS.<!-- linebreak -->
</p>

<p> Yeast model: <me>y_{t+1} = f(y_t)</me>
</p>

<p> Drug model: <me>M_{t+1} = f(M_t)</me>
</p>

</paragraphs>

<paragraphs xml:id="deriving-the-doubling-time">
<title>Deriving the doubling time</title>

<p> Combing our knowledge of exponential and
logarithmic functions, we can derive the doubling time formula from the
solution that describes the dynamics of the yeast model above.
</p>

</paragraphs>
